<Layout
  title="OpenSource type system | Maxim McNair"
  desc="Build a type system with opensource typefaces"
>
  <main>
    <section>
      <h1 class="opentype-title">OSS Type System</h1>
      <h3 class="opentype-subtitle">
        Build a Type System with Open Source Typefaces
      </h3>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h3>Why use Open Source Typefaces?</h3>
      <p>
        This site focuses on open source typefaces that you can host yourself
        and don't need to inject a script you don't control. They're a great
        start for your next open source project.
      </p>
      <p>
        The CSS created will import all these typefaces with consistent font
        style, so 600 will be bold for each typeface.
      </p>
      <p>
        There are a number of type scale tools around the web. Notable Jeremy
        Church's <a href="https://type-scale.com/" target="_blank">Type Scale</a
        > and Tim Brownâ€™s
        <a href="https://www.modularscale.com/" target="_blank">Modular Scale</a
        >. However these focus on just the type scale (type sizes) and not a
        cohesive system with spacing and type pairs.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you have any comments or suggestions you can either tweet me at <a
          href="https://twitter.com/maximmcnair"
          target="_blank">@maximmcnair</a
        > or create an <a>issue</a>/<a>PR</a> on Github.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h3>Typefaces Options & Weights</h3>
      <p>
        It's a great time for open source typefaces, as many big players such as
        Adobe, IBM and Github have created and open sourced typefaces anyone can
        use.
      </p>
      <p>
        This selection of typefaces are intended for use in interfaces and the
        surrounding online documentation, rather than for marketing.
      </p>
      <p>
        We use a subset of the weights these typefaces have, sticking to just <em
          >Thin</em
        >, <em>Medium</em> and <em>Bold</em>. Take a look at their source code
        to play around to explored their additional weights.
      </p>
      <p>Click on the weights below each typeface to view them.</p>
      <div class="typeface-options">
        <OpenTypeWeights client:load />
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h3>Typefaces pairs</h3>
      <p>
        Here are a number of type pairs to start with. You can create your own
        by clicking the settings button (you've need javascript enable for
        this).
      </p>
      <p>
        We use a safe default by using seperate typefaces for <strong
          >title</strong
        > and <strong>body</strong> styles.
      </p>
      <OpenTypePairs client:load />
    </section>

    <section>
      <h3>Type scale</h3>
      <p>
        Built upon the scales set out in Robert Bringhurst's <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Elements_of_Typographic_Style"
          >The Elements of Typographic Style</a
        > (turn to p45 & p147 if you have this classic to hand).
      </p>

      <OpenTypeScale client:load />
    </section>

    <section>
      <h3>Preview</h3>
      <OpenTypePreview client:load />
    </section>

    <section>
      <OpenTypeCSS client:load />
    </section>
  </main>

  <BuiltBy />
</Layout>

